The advancement of Vehicle-to-Everything (V2X) communication is pivotal in the deployment of Intelligent Transportation Systems (ITS), offering significant improvements in road safety and traffic management. Current systems predominantly utilize pseudonym-based approaches to address privacy concerns; however, these systems confront several limitations, including reliance on centralized authorization authorities and insufficient support for practical scenarios where there is a need to disclose certain necessary attributes. In this paper, we introduce PSP, a novel privacy-preserving, self-certify pseudonym protocol explicitly designed for V2X networks that support selective disclosure. PSP employs an anonymous credential framework, facilitating decentralized pseudonym generation and eliminating dependence on central authorities. This innovative approach (1) supports decentralized pseudonym generation and binding, eliminating the reliance on a centralized Authorization Authority. (2) restricts vehicles to binding only one pseudonym with their long-term credential per epoch, thereby thwarting Sybil attacks; (3) enables vehicles to selectively disclose the necessary attributes while safeguarding credential privacy; and (4) incorporates credential tracing and revocation mechanisms to ensure accountability for malicious activities. We substantiate our contributions with formal security analysis and demonstrate the practicality of PSP through implementation, achieving efficient proof generation and verification times suitable for real-time ITS applications.